Oh yes, and there was a - a wonderful character - in our denomination, he was a deacon as well, but this is when we were down in - Coalyard Row, the beginning of that, and - they had
 a farm higher up than where we were living, but he had the stables by our house. By our house, and - he looked after I believe the - horses, belonging to the - colliery, and his own and some of the cows there and they used to milk there, and - on the wee
k
night meeting perhaps he wouldn't have time to go up to - to his own home, he'd come in to our house and my sister I suppose, I don't remember it then, my old - eldest sister - he'd ask her - Mary, wipe a bit of my face my dear will you? And - brush a bit
 
of my beard Mary. I haven't got to me to go home. So - right, so my sister was washing his face, and brushing his hair and his beard, and she noticed - he had a rip in his trousers, and she said, you've got a rip in your trousers. Never mind Mary, God won
't look at my trousers, and I'll put my cap on it, he says, for other people not to see it. And he was a wonderful character. And - I told you didn't I about the time he brought the milk to my mother's did I? A can}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
