\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1779283 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11094101\charrsid12984966 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1661656 OP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11094101\charrsid12984966 She would g
o to my - aunt's, to Maesteg I think it was you know. But - I don't know, it's other people who visit - who were visiting us mostly. I remember one time - my aunt was living - he was - my - her husband, my - my mother's sister's husband was a mining engin
e
er - and - sinking the pits, and he was sinking the pit somewhere up in - I couldn't ex - exactly I think it's up in - Treharris or up that way somewhere, up the Rhondda, and - he was - very fond of his drink. And I suppose if he had been very nasty to my
 
aunt and the children. So she brought them all to my mother's one night. Seven children. And my mother put them up. Well for how long I don't remember. Well there you are, I don't know, but they didn't care how - how they'd be, just to have a - you know, 
a
 home for the night sort of thing you know. Yes, I don't know how long they stayed but I remember my mother saying that, that she - they came there with seven children, she had - she had had nineteen children. Mm. But I think it was about fourteen she rea
red. Mm.
